<TITLE> China raps more than 5,000 officials over coal mines </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, June 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - More than 5,000 Chinese civil servants involved in supervising the world's deadliest coal mines have been punished for involvement in almost 100,000 cases of illegal mining since 2005, Xinhua news agency said. Coal mine accidents kill on average 17 people a day in China as owners, often in collusion with government officials, push production to the limit to meet demand from the booming economy. "By the end of 2006, China had investigated 89,926 cases of mining with no licence, 1,907 cases involving illegal trading of prospecting and mining rights, and 5,795 cases of mining beyond boundary lines," Jia Qihai, a senior official with the Ministry of Land and Resources, was quoted as saying. Xinhua said the tally was recorded "since 2005". It did not say how the offending bureaucrats had been punished. China has been cracking down on illegal mining since the State Council, the nation's cabinet, demanded a cleanout in August 2005. "Generally speaking, the number of cases of illegal mining is declining sharply and mine resources are exploited in a more orderly manner," Jia was quoted as saying. "Officials in some regions still haven't realised the graveness of the situation and supervision and institutional construction remains wea
